  <worksheets>
    <worksheet name='Cost grid'>
      <layout-options>
        <title>
          <formatted-text>
            <run>Environmental cost of one AI model at scale</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </title>
        <caption>
          <formatted-text>
            <run>Per-prompt energy, water, and carbon for the selected model, scaled to 1, 50, and 100 billion prompts. Each cell pairs the raw aggregate (large) with an everyday equivalence (smaller). Equivalence factors from Jegham et al.: 11 MWh average annual U.S. household consumption, 2,500 kL Olympic swimming pool, ~60 tCO₂e per transatlantic flight. The 100 B-scale energy figures use a derived value because the upstream snapshot has a 10× multiplier defect on three columns (energy MWh, household equiv. MWh, university equiv. MWh); other 100 B figures in this view audit cleanly.</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </caption>
      </layout-options>
      <table>
        <view>
          <datasources>
            <datasource caption='c5_aggregate_scaling' name='federated.0xoq8v90e8sivi17taauj1bmbiu6' />
            <datasource name='Parameters' />
          </datasources>
          <datasource-dependencies datasource='Parameters'>
            <column caption='Selected Model' datatype='string' name='[Parameter 1]' param-domain-type='list' role='measure' type='nominal' value='&quot;GPT-4o (Aug)&quot;'>
              <calculation class='tableau' formula='&quot;GPT-4o (Aug)&quot;' />
            </column>
          </datasource-dependencies>
          <datasource-dependencies datasource='federated.0xoq8v90e8sivi17taauj1bmbiu6'>
